Additionally, the U.S. Food and Drug Administration (FDA) classifies MSG as a generally recognized as safe (GRAS) substance, meaning that it has a long history of safe use in food. The FDA also notes that many people who believe they have a sensitivity to MSG may actually be reacting to other components of the food, such as other flavorings or ingredients, rather than to the MSG itself.
However, it's worth noting that some individuals may still have an intolerance or sensitivity to MSG, and it's always a good idea to pay attention to how your body reacts to different foods and to talk to a doctor if you have concerns. In general, moderate consumption of MSG is considered safe for most people.

Additionally, the U.S. Food and Drug Administration (FDA) classifies MSG as a generally recognized as safe (GRAS) substance, meaning that it has a long history of safe use in food. The FDA also notes that many people who believe they have a sensitivity to MSG may actually be reacting to other components of the food, such as other flavorings or ingredients, rather than to the MSG itself.
However, it's worth noting that some individuals may still have an intolerance or sensitivity to MSG, and it's always a good idea to pay attention to how your body reacts to different foods and to talk to a doctor if you have concerns. In general, moderate consumption of MSG is considered safe for most people.

Additionally, the U.S. Food and Drug Administration (FDA) classifies MSG as a generally recognized as safe (GRAS) substance, meaning that it has a long history of safe use in food. The FDA also notes that many people who believe they have a sensitivity to MSG may actually be reacting to other components of the food, such as other flavorings or ingredients, rather than to the MSG itself.
However, it's worth noting that some individuals may still have an intolerance or sensitivity to MSG, and it's always a good idea to pay attention to how your body reacts to different foods and to talk to a doctor if you have concerns. In general, moderate consumption of MSG is considered safe for most people.

Additionally, the U.S. Food and Drug Administration (FDA) classifies MSG as a generally recognized as safe (GRAS) substance, meaning that it has a long history of safe use in food. The FDA also notes that many people who believe they have a sensitivity to MSG may actually be reacting to other components of the food, such as other flavorings or ingredients, rather than to the MSG itself.
However, it's worth noting that some individuals may still have an intolerance or sensitivity to MSG, and it's always a good idea to pay attention to how your body reacts to different foods and to talk to a doctor if you have concerns. In general, moderate consumption of MSG is considered safe for most people.
